answer.p:
If we take any invertible 2 \times 2 matrix P and define B=P\inv AP, then B will be similar to A.
          For example, let's take
          P=\mat{-8 3;5 -2}
          and then let


              B=P\inv AP


              \quad=\mat{-2 -3;-5 -8}\mat{1 2; 3 4}\mat{-8 3;5 -2}


              \quad=\mat{8 -1;22 -3}


          It is quite obvious that there are infinitely many matrices that are similar to A because we could perform this procedure using any
invertible matrix P.
